    Introduction
    
     A samurai must first and foremost constantly remember - remember day and night, from the morning he takes chopsticks to taste the New Year's feast, to the last night of the old year, when he pays his debts - that he must die. This is his main business.
    If he always remembers this, he will be able to live his life in accordance with loyalty and filial piety, avoid a myriad of evils and misfortunes, protect himself from sickness and hardship, and enjoy a long life.
    He will be an exceptional person, endowed with excellent qualities. For life is fleeting, like a drop of evening dew and morning frost, and all the more so is the life of a warrior.
    
     Right and Wrong
    A warrior must deeply understand these two qualities. If he knows how to do one and avoid the other, he has found the way of the samurai.
    Right and wrong are nothing other than good and evil, and although I do not deny that the distinction between these words is slight, to act rightly and do good is considered tiresome, while to act wrongly and do evil is considered easy and pleasant, and so naturally many are inclined toward the wrong or evil and do not love the right and good.
    The reason for this is the inability to master oneself. By itself this may not sound so bad, but if we look deeper, we will see that everything stems from cowardice. Therefore I assert that it is necessary for a samurai to refrain from wrong and strive toward right.
    
     The Choice of Friends
    The most important thing for a samurai in service - to associate and make friends only among those comrades who are brave, loyal to duty, intelligent and influential.
    But since such people are few, one should among many friends choose one upon whom, if necessary, he can completely rely.
    In general, it is desirable for a samurai to make close friends from among those whom he loves and with whom he prefers to eat, drink and travel.
    
     Friendship
    Reliability is one of the qualities of the Way of the Warrior, necessary for a samurai, but in no way is it desirable to offer help without good reason, to get involved in matters that are of no importance or to undertake obligations in things that do not concern you yourself, only for the sake of doing this or giving advice.
    Even if the matter concerns you to some degree, it is better to remain aloof if no one has asked you to intervene.
    
     Various Matters
    It is wrong to think that you cannot achieve all that great masters have achieved. Masters are people, and so are you.
    If you know that you can become like them, you are already on the path to doing so.
    
    A warrior should never speak uncertainly. A warrior should prepare himself for everything beforehand. Even in everyday matters the depths of the soul are revealed.
    
    The priest Tanner said: "The prudent servant does not seek a higher position. Meanwhile, foolish people are rarely promoted in rank."
    
    Truly, the life of a man lasts but a moment, so live and do as you wish. It is foolish to live in this world, like a dream, meeting troubles every day and doing only what you dislike.
    I personally love to sleep. With time I intend to retire to my home more and more often and spend the rest of my life sleeping.
    
    The basic principle of martial arts is to attack without thinking of life and death. If the opponent does the same, you and he are equals. In this case, the outcome of the duel is decided by strength of spirit and fate.
    
    Nakano Jinemon said: "The study of such subjects as military tactics is useless. If a warrior does not rush at the enemy and cut him down with closed eyes, he will be useless, because he will not advance a single step in battle." Iyanaga Sasuke was of the same opinion.
    
    If a man conducted himself with dignity before death, he is truly a brave man. We know many examples of such people. He who boasts of his daring but falls into confusion before death cannot be called truly brave.
    
     The End
    Every samurai, great or small, of high rank or low, must first and foremost think of how to meet the inevitable death.
    However intelligent and talented he may be, if he is negligent and not sufficiently calm-headed, and therefore, finding himself face to face with death, appears confused, all his previous good deeds will lose their meaning, all decent people will despise him, and upon him will fall an indelible stain of shame.
    
    For if a samurai goes into battle, commits brave and magnificent deeds and covers his name with glory, it is only because he has set his heart on death.
    If the worst happens and he is destined to part with life, then when his opponent asks his name, he should answer it loudly and clearly and bid farewell to life with a smile on his lips, showing not the slightest sign of fear.
    
    If he is severely wounded, so that no healer can help him, then, as befits a samurai, while still conscious, he should answer the questions of his commanders and comrades and tell them how he received his wound, after which he should calmly, without any ceremony, face death.
    
    Although the samurai must first and foremost honor the Way of the Samurai, there is no doubt that we are all negligent. Therefore, if one should ask today: "What is the true meaning of the Way of the Samurai?", only a few would answer without hesitation.
    This is because no one prepares himself beforehand to answer such questions. This shows that people have forgotten the Way. Negligence is dangerous.